rn challenges. The contributors show how contemporary poverty is forged in neighborhoods, argue that discrimination in housing markets is a profound source of poverty, suggest that gender inequalities in the family and in the social evaluation of the caretaking role remain a hidden dimension of inequality, and develop the argument that contemporary inequality is best understood as an inequality in fundamental human capabilities. This book demonstrates in manifold ways how contemporary scholarship and policy must be recast to make sense of new and emerging forms of poverty and social exclusion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aEquality. 0aMarginality, Social. 0aPoverty. 0aSocial classes. 0aSocial policy. 4aEconomics -- Social Economics. 4aSociology -- Global Issues, Economy, and Work. 4aSociology -- Race, Class, and Gender. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Poverty & Homelessness.2bisacsh1 aBourguignon, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFineman, Martha Albertson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrusky, David B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrusky, David B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKanbur, Ravi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKanbur, Ravi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMassey, Douglas S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNussbaum, Martha C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSen, Amartya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilson, William Julius, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476759040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97808047675